slides.title: General network
slides.text: There are seven modularity classes. The largest class is the one with violet color (31%), followed by the green (16%), and the blue (16%). Each of them represents different communities around the topic of gendered online harassment.

slides.title: Violet cluster - Feminism and experts in LatinAmerica and Spain
slides.text: This cluster has a central node (in=2; out=87), which is a Chilean blog about feminism. The blog points to many different sources of feminism content, many of them written in Spanish and located in SouthAmerica, a few are located in Spain. There are blogs, organizations, and experts such as judges (Mujeresjuezas.es) and journalists (Periodistasdeapie.org.mx).

slides.title: Green cluster - Open source and Internet rights
slides.text: There are three main nodes: www.tedic.org (in=2 ; out=21), Codingrights.org (in=4 ; out=16); Feministinternet.org (in=5 ; out=13). Tedic is an NGO based in Paraguay that develops open-source civic technology and defends digital rights and free Internet culture. Codingrights is a female-led Think-and-Do tank based in Brazil created to promote Human Rights through Code. Feministinternet is an initiative that has created a set of statements for internet-related rights, it is led by the association for progressive communications.

slides.title: Blue cluster - Women and equality in Spain
slides.text: There is a main node: www.fundacionmujeres.es (in= 2; out=13). This is an association that strives to provide equal opportunities for women. In general, the actors in this cluster describe themselves in terms of equality, human rights, women, and progressivism. There are associations and public institutions. None is specifically dealing with gendered issues in digital contexts, and only a few of them tap on these issues (e.g. Observatorioviolencia.org). Many references to entrepreneurship, a few references to feminism.

slides.title: Orange cluster - Global feminism, policies, and tech
slides.text: There are two main nodes: Takebackthetech.net (in= 4; out=41) and Genderit.org (in=5; out=10). Techbackthetach is a global campaign project on online gender-based violence. Genderit is a project on feminist reflections on Internet policies. There are projects and associations dealing with digital rights, also in the context of media businesses (e.g. journalism). The association for progressive communications is also in this cluster.

slides.title: 5. Yellow cluster - Online bullying in Spanish
slides.text: There are two main nodes: Takebackthetech.net/es (in= 1; out=8) and fundacionaprenderamirar.Wordpress.com (in= 1; out=7). La Fundacion "Aprender a mirar" strives for defending children and teenagers in the digital world. Many of the nodes in this cluster deal with scholar cyberbullying. A few specifically deal with more general topics, such as gender-based online violence ( Stopviolenciadegenerodigital.com).
